Quits: Total Nonfarm

quits <- fredr(series_id = "JTSQUL",
                       observation_start = as.Date("2000-12-01"),
                       observation_end = as.Date("2023-12-01")) %>%
  dplyr::select(date, series_id, value) %>%
  mutate(quits_first_diff = value - lag(value),
         quits_second_diff = difference(value, differences = 2)) %>%
  tsibble(index = date)
quits$quits <- quits$value

Graph of levels

quit_graph <- ggplot(quits) + theme_bw() + 
  geom_line(aes(x=date, y= quits),
            linewidth = 1.1) +
  ylab("Quits") +
  xlab("Date") +
  ggtitle("Quits Data (JOLTS)")

ggsave("quits.pdf", quit_graph, dpi = 300, width = 10, height = 8, bg = "white")

Producing a summary statistics table

data_frames_list <- list(quits,emp_fam,fed_funds,eggs)
selected_variables <- c("quits","emp_fam","fed_funds","eggs")
summary_stats_list <- list()
for (i in seq_along(data_frames_list)) {
  for (variable in selected_variables) {
    current_variable <- data_frames_list[[i]][[variable]]
    
    if (is.numeric(current_variable)) {
      summary_stats <- c(
        Mean = mean(current_variable, na.rm = TRUE),
        SD = sd(current_variable, na.rm = TRUE),
        Min = min(current_variable, na.rm = TRUE),
        Max = max(current_variable, na.rm = TRUE),
        N = sum(!is.na(current_variable))
      )
      
      summary_stats_list[[paste(names(data_frames_list)[i], variable, sep = "_")]] <- summary_stats
    }
  }
}

combined_table <- do.call(cbind, summary_stats_list)
combined_df <- as.data.frame(combined_table)
latex_table <- xtable(combined_df)
print(latex_table)

Forcasting: Questions 4,5,6

Select two of your series and split them into a training set (T-6 observations) and a forecast comparison (test) set (6 observations). Using the training set and ARIMA framework, choose the best model for each series (remember these are univariate models). Provide a table with your preferred specification and at least two alternatives for each model. Discuss why you chose the model you did, make sure you use all available information to state your case. Things you should be thinking about (and discussing in your report!) while choosing your model are the model fit statistics, the presence of serial correlation (indicating model misspecification), and seasonality. Give me a clear and concise roadmap for how you arrived at the model you did.

#looking at the loss functions
loss_functions <- function(predict, actual) {
predict <- as.vector(predict)
actual <- as.vector(actual)
mse <- mean((predict-actual)^2)
mae <- mean(abs(predict-actual))
mape <- mean(abs((predict-actual)/actual)*100)
msle <- mean((log(actual) - log(predict) )^2)
return(list(mse = mse,
mae = mae,
mape = mape,
msle = msle))
}


losses_1 <- loss_functions(pred_mod_fem_1$mean, test_fem)
losses_2 <- loss_functions(pred_mod_fem_2$mean, test_fem)
losses_3 <- loss_functions(pred_mod_fem_3$mean, test_fem)

forecast_3 <- forecast(pred_mod_fem_3, h = 6, xreg = xreg_forecast)
forecast_data <- data.frame(Date = seq.Date(as.Date("2023-07-01"),
as.Date("2023-12-01"),
'months'),
test = exp(test_fem),
forecast_1 = exp(forecast_1$mean),
forecast_2 = exp(forecast_2$mean),
forecast_3 = exp(forecast_3$mean)) %>%
as_tsibble(index = Date)


comb_object <- foreccomb(observed_vector = forecast_data$test,
                         prediction_matrix = forecast_data[,-c(1,2)])
avg_forecast <- comb_SA(comb_object)


ols_forecast <- comb_OLS(comb_object)


combined_forecast_values <- ((ols_forecast$Weights[1] * forecast_1$mean)/sum(ols_forecast$Weights) + 
                            (ols_forecast$Weights[2] * forecast_1$mean)/sum(ols_forecast$Weights)  + 
                            (ols_forecast$Weights[3] * forecast_1$mean)/sum(ols_forecast$Weights) )


#MSE(combined_forecast_values, test_fem)
#MAE(combined_forecast_values, test_fem)

new_fem <- ts(combined_forecast_values, start = end(train_fem) + 1, frequency = frequency(train_fem))

# Combine the original time series with the forecasted values
combined_fem <- c(train_fem, new_fem)

combined_fem <- ts(combined_fem,  start = c(2000,12), freq = 12)

forecast_data <- forecast(combined_fem, h = 6)


combined_fem_plot <- autoplot(combined_fem) +
  autolayer(forecast_data, series = "Forecast") +
  autolayer(forecast_data$upper[,2], series = "Upper 99% Confidence Band") +  # Upper 99% Confidence Band
  autolayer(forecast_data$lower[,2], series = "Lower 99% Confidence Band", alpha = 0.25) +  # Lower 99% Confidence Band
  autolayer(forecast_data$upper[,1], series = "Upper 95% Confidence Band") +  # Upper 95% Confidence Band
  autolayer(forecast_data$lower[,1], series = "Lower 95% Confidence Band", alpha = 0.25) +  # Lower 95% Confidence Band
  ylab("Forecasted Unemployment for Women with Families")

#calculating loss functions
loss_functions <- function(predict, actual) {
predict <- as.vector(predict)
actual <- as.vector(actual)
mse <- mean((predict-actual)^2)
mae <- mean(abs(predict-actual))
mape <- mean(abs((predict-actual)/actual)*100)
msle <- mean((log(actual) - log(predict) )^2)
return(list(mse = mse,
mae = mae,
mape = mape,
msle = msle))
}


losses_1 <- loss_functions(pred_mod_eggs_1$mean, test_eggs)
losses_2 <- loss_functions(pred_mod_eggs_2$mean, test_eggs)
losses_3 <- loss_functions(pred_mod_eggs_3$mean, test_eggs)

forecast_1 <- forecast(pred_mod_eggs_1, h = 6, xreg = xreg_forecast)
forecast_2 <- forecast(pred_mod_eggs_2, h = 6, xreg = xreg_forecast)
forecast_3 <- forecast(pred_mod_eggs_3, h = 6, xreg = xreg_forecast)
forecast_data <- data.frame(Date = seq.Date(as.Date("2023-07-01"),
as.Date("2023-12-01"),
'months'),
test = exp(test_eggs),
forecast_1 = exp(forecast_1$mean),
forecast_2 = exp(forecast_2$mean),
forecast_3 = exp(forecast_3$mean)) %>%
as_tsibble(index = Date)




comb_object_eggs <- foreccomb(observed_vector = forecast_data$test,
                         prediction_matrix = forecast_data[,-c(1,2)])
avg_forecast_eggs <- comb_SA(comb_object_eggs)


ols_forecast_eggs <- comb_OLS(comb_object_eggs)


combined_forecast_values_eggs <- ((ols_forecast_eggs$Weights[1] * forecast_1$mean)/sum(ols_forecast_eggs$Weights) + 
                            (ols_forecast_eggs$Weights[2] * forecast_1$mean)/sum(ols_forecast$Weights)  + 
                            (ols_forecast_eggs$Weights[3] * forecast_1$mean)/sum(ols_forecast$Weights) )

# Create a time series object for the combined forecasted values
new_eggs <- ts(combined_forecast_values_eggs, start = end(train_fem) + 1, frequency = frequency(train_eggs))

# Combine the original time series with the forecasted values
combined_eggs <- c(train_eggs, new_eggs)

combined_eggs <- ts(combined_eggs,  start = c(2000,12), freq = 12)

forecast_data <- forecast(combined_eggs, h = 6)

combined_egg_plot <- autoplot(combined_eggs) +
  autolayer(forecast_data, series = "Forecast") +
  autolayer(forecast_data$upper[,2], series = "Upper 99% Confidence Band") +  
  autolayer(forecast_data$lower[,2], series = "Lower 99% Confidence Band", alpha = 0.25) +
  autolayer(forecast_data$upper[,1], series = "Upper 95% Confidence Band") +
  autolayer(forecast_data$lower[,1], series = "Lower 95% Confidence Band", alpha = 0.25) +
  ylab("Egg Prices Forecast")


ggsave("combined_egg_plot.pdf", combined_egg_plot, dpi = 300, width = 10, height = 8, bg = "white")
